{"amendments":[{"body":"src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:463-487, src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:250-258, and src/adapters/fs.rs:2526-2602: `record_bead_start` writes a running lineage row before it proves the milestone can legally leave a terminal state. Starting a bead on a `completed` or `abandoned` milestone appends `task-runs.ndjson`, then the second reconcile fails because terminal snapshots cannot have an active bead. The call returns an error after mutating lineage, so later start attempts fail until some out-of-band finalize/manual cleanup removes that stray running row. Reject terminal milestones before `record_task_run_start`, or make the lineage and snapshot update atomic.","rationale":"This is a real partial-write corruption path on a normal API call, and the current retry/repair flow does not automatically recover from it."},{"body":"src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:470-487 and 593-614 together with src/adapters/fs.rs:2536-2602 and 2617-2832: the milestone snapshot is recomputed and written outside the task-run lock. That leaves a lost-update window where one thread can read lineage, another thread can start or finalize a different bead, and the first thread then overwrites `status.json` with stale `active_bead` and progress counters. Example: A finalizes bead-1 and computes `Ready`; B starts bead-2 and persists `Active`; A then writes `Ready`, hiding the active run even though `task-runs.ndjson` says bead-2 is still running. The lineage file is protected, but the snapshot is not, so milestone state is still not concurrency-safe.","rationale":"The patch adds explicit locking and idempotency for concurrent/replayed runs, so this remaining cross-file race is a correctness gap in the robustness story."}],"summary":"Reviewed the diff against origin/master, read the milestone lineage model/service/FS adapter code end-to-end, and ran `cargo test milestone_record -- --nocapture` successfully. I found two correctness issues: a partial-write path when starting work on a terminal milestone, and a cross-file lost-update race that can leave `status.json` out of sync with `task-runs.ndjson` under concurrent operations."}